images.summary: This detail shows a sandwich wall with a 10-inch concrete wall reinforced with 25 MPa poured concrete. The wall includes 2-inch rigid insulation and is reinforced with 10M horizontal rebar on each side and 10M vertical rebar spaced at 24 inches on center. The wall is supported by a 24-inch wide by 8-inch thick footing made of 20 MPa concrete with two runs of 15M rebar. The footing is embedded 4 inches into undisturbed soil, suitable for a 3000 PSF bearing capacity. An anchor bolt detail (A1) specifies a 1-inch anchor bolt welded to a 'U' at 48 inches on center. The wall includes a typical stud wall, sill plate on sill gasket, and 1x4 strapping at 24 inches on center. The base trim drip cap is also noted. The scale of the drawing is 1/2 inch equals 1 foot.

The wall includes a sill plate on a sill gasket and is anchored with 1/2-inch anchor bolts at 48 inches on center. Reinforcement consists of continuous 15M rebar at the top of the wall, with horizontal and vertical 15M rebar spaced at 16 inches on center. The wall features 2-inch rigid insulation below the cooler floor and extends to 28 inches below grade. The footing is 36 inches by 12 inches, reinforced with three continuous 15M rebars and 15M transversal bars at 16 inches on center. The structure bears on native material suitable for a 3000 PSF bearing capacity. The scale is 1/2 inch equals 1 foot.

images.summary: This foundation plan section details the construction of retaining walls and wall FW 2. The wall includes a sill plate on a sill gasket with 1/2-inch anchor bolts spaced at 48 inches on center. Two 15M continuous rebars are placed at the top of the wall. The wall features 15M verticals at 16 inches on center on both faces with 2-inch cover, and 15M horizontal bars at the same spacing. The concrete slab is reinforced with 6x6x6 welded wire mesh.

images.summary: This detail illustrates the installation of 2x6 diagonal braces on the ground floor. The braces are to be continuous and end at the stud connection to the plate. They should not be notched into studs and must be installed at approximately 45-degree angles. Minimum nail spacing is specified at 1 1/2 inches. Double solid blocking between studs is fastened with six 3 1/2-inch nails through the face and three nails through the stud into each end of each block. Each brace requires twelve 3 1/2-inch common spiral nails at the top and bottom of the wall. Additional details include 3-ply solid blocking and wedge anchors at each brace location.

images.summary: This detail provides specifications for wind column installation on the ground floor. The wind column is supported by a 36x36x12-inch thick footing, with provisions for slotted holes for 15M hairpins. The wall is thickened to 14 inches at the wind column, with a chamfered top. Double 15M hairpins are used, and the floor slab is thickened to 8 inches at hairpin locations. The detail includes a 6x14x1/2-inch steel plate with 16 3/4-inch thru bolts, and a C6x8.2 channel. Double top plates and engineered trusses are part of the assembly. The baseplate is specified as 14 inches by the column depth plus 1/2 inch by 3/4 inch, with sleeve anchors embedded 6 inches.

images.summary: This image presents a wall schedule detailing six different wall types (W1 to W6) for the ground floor framing plan. Each wall type specifies the materials and construction methods, including cladding, air barriers, O.S.B. sheathing, stud sizes and spacing, solid blocking, insulation (R 22 Roxul Bats), and additional layers such as poly and liners. For instance, W1 includes 29 gauge steel exterior cladding and PVC, AGTUFF liner, while W2 features 1" pine barn board siding. The schedule provides comprehensive specifications for constructing walls with varying materials and structural components, ensuring the building's integrity and performance.

images.element_type: Notes for Bracing of Roof Truss
images.text_verbatim:
NOTES FOR BRACING OF ROOF TRUSS
1 -- >> CONTRACTOR AND OWNER TO NOTIFY ENGINEER OF ANY TRUSS DEFICIENCIES SUCH AS DAMAGED OR BROKEN TRUSSES, WARPING OF TRUSS MEMBERS, AND MISSING OR OFFSET TRUSS PLATES.
2 -- >> DIAGONAL BRACING MUST BE PROVIDED ON ALL WEB MEMBERS THAT REQUIRE LATERAL BRACING. DIAGONAL BRACING SHALL BE SPACED AS NOTED ON THE ATTACHED DRAWINGS & X-BRACING SHALL BE PROVIDED @ ENDWALLS @ INTERVALS NOTED BY THE ENGINEER.
3 -- >> PERMANENT LATERAL BRACING TO BE INSTALLED ON WEB MEMBERS AS INDICATED BY ENGINEER.
4 -->> PROVIDE DIAGONAL BRACING @ ALL DISCONTINUITIES IN LATERAL BRACING SUCH AS WHERE TRUSS TYPE CHANGES
5 -->> THE TRUSS SUPPLIER SHALL DESIGN THE TRUSSES FOR THE BRACING NOTED. BRACING DETAILS WILL NOT BE MODIFIED UNLESS SPECIFIED BY THE ENGINEER.
images.summary: This image contains notes for the bracing of roof trusses. Key instructions include notifying the engineer of any truss deficiencies such as damage or warping. Diagonal bracing is required on all web members needing lateral bracing, with specific spacing and X-bracing at endwalls as noted by the engineer. Permanent lateral bracing must be installed as indicated, and diagonal bracing should be provided at all discontinuities in lateral bracing. The truss supplier is responsible for designing the trusses for the specified bracing, and modifications to bracing details are only allowed if specified by the engineer.

images.element_type: Notes for Bracing of Roof Truss
images.text_verbatim:
SPACING AS SPECIFIED BY BRACE DESIGNER 48'-0" MAXIMUM
2x4 DIAGONAL BRACING SPACED AS REQUIRED BY THE BRACING DESIGNER
2x4 STRUT x 5'-0" LONG @ TOP & BOTTOM WITH TWO OF 3 1/2" NAILS @ EACH TRUSS WEB MEMBER
ANCHOR 2x4 DIAGONAL BRACE TO LATERAL WITH FOUR OF 3 1/2" NAILS @ INTERSECTION OF TRUSS WEB & TRUSS LATERAL
BUTT 2x4 LATERALS @ ALL SPLICE LOCATIONS. ENSURE BUTT JOINT IS TIGHT & CENTERED ON TRUSS WEB.
LAP 2x4 DIAGONAL (Min. 2 TRUSSES) TO ENSURE DIAGONAL BRACE EXTENDS COMPLETELY FROM TOP CHORD TO BOTTOM CHORD OF TRUSS. { AS REQUIRED }
ANCHOR DIAGONAL BRACE TO STRUT @ BOTH ENDS WITH FOUR OF 3 1/2" NAILS
images.summary: This image provides detailed notes on the bracing of roof trusses. The spacing for bracing is specified by the brace designer, with a maximum of 48'-0". Diagonal bracing using 2x4s is required, with specific instructions for struts and anchoring. Struts are 5'-0" long and secured with nails at each truss web member. Diagonal braces must be anchored to laterals with nails at intersections, and butt joints for laterals should be tight and centered. Diagonal braces should lap over a minimum of two trusses to ensure complete extension from the top to the bottom chord. Anchoring of diagonal braces to struts is specified at both ends.
